<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900402-0031</DOCNO><DOCID>900402-0031.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>04/02/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   THE SOVIET UNION SENT military reinforcements toLithuania's capital.   As the breakaway Baltic republic's legislature met toconsider its next moves, dozens of Soviet military vehicleslumbered through the streets of Vilnius, and the last Westernjournalists were ousted from the republic on orders from theSoviet government. The activity prompted some Lithuanians toexpress concern about an impending Kremlin militarycrackdown. On Saturday, Gorbachev had urged the republic torenounce its March 11 proclamation of independence and toenter talks with Moscow.</LP><TEXT>   Lithuania's president rejected Gorbachev's appeal, butsaid the republic would send negotiators to Moscow today toarrange talks with Soviet officials.   ---   THATCHER BLAMED extremists for turning a tax protest intoa riot.   The British prime minister, as well as oppositionpoliticians, criticized &quot;extreme groups who used violence&quot;for the &quot;mayhem&quot; that erupted Saturday at an anti-tax protestin London. More than 130 people were injured and about 340arrested in the rioting, considered the worst in decades.Sporadic unrest flared yesterday as the unpopular tax, whichgenerally replaces a property tax with a levy on each adult,took effect in England and Wales. Thatcher made clear shewon't back down over the issue.   About 300 inmates rioted at an overcrowded prison inManchester, England, occupying rooftops and setting fires.About 50 people were injured.   ---   East Berlin officials warned that a Bundesbank proposalfor a 2-to-1 conversion rate for East German marks into WestGerman marks could hinder the unification of the twoGermanys. The recommendation marked a retreat from pledgesmade by Bonn's leader during recent East German elections.   ---   Mandela offered to meet with South Africa's President deKlerk to discuss how to end violence, but said police conductwould determine when the African National Congress holdstalks with the government. The black nationalist leaderindicated that there were differences within the ANC, whichcanceled April 11 negotiations with Pretoria.   ---   Police in China barred the general public from enteringBeijing's Tiananmen Square, where dissidents had urged asilent protest against last year's government crackdown onstudent-led demonstrations. Paramilitary forces ringed mostof the huge square in the latest sign of tightened securityin the capital ahead of anniversaries marking unrest.   ---   Idaho Gov. Andrus vetoed what would have been the nation'smost restrictive abortion law. The legislation would haveprevented about 95% of the state's abortions. Friday's vetoby Andrus, considered an opponent of abortion, leftanti-abortion leaders searching for new opportunities topress their efforts before the Supreme Court.   ---   Hundreds of civilians in Lebanon fled the country'sChristian enclave as a cease-fire ended two days of fightingbetween rival Christian forces. More than 60 people werekilled and about 130 injured in the battles. The truce, the15th in two months of fighting, was negotiated by athree-member mediation committee backed by the Vatican.   ---   Cases of venereal disease are rebounding at gay clinics inLos Angeles, Seattle and Denver, and the rate of newAIDS-virus infections in Chicago has risen for the first timein five years. The increases were attributed by some to areturn to unsafe-sex practices within the homosexualcommunity and elsewhere.   ---   Medical researchers reported that damage from spinal-cordinjuries, frequently the cause of paralysis, can be reducedby a common generic drug. Such injuries afflict about 10,000people a year. Researchers said that large doses ofmethylprednisolone, an anti-inflammatory drug, given withineight hours of injury can limit damage.   ---   Zimbabwe's President Mugabe vowed to press ahead withplans to turn the nation's democracy into a one-party stateafter results from last week's elections gave the country'sruling party all but three of the 150 seats in Harare'slegislature. But the 66-year-old Mugabe indicated thatopposition parties wouldn't be immediately outlawed.   ---   Honduras's military pledged to search for gunmen whoattacked a bus carrying 28 U.S. airmen about six miles northof Tegucigalpa, leaving eight wounded, at least twoseriously. A leftist rebel group, the Morazano NationalLiberation Front, claimed responsibility for the assaultSaturday.</TEXT></DOC>